                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Kebkeck</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#e9e9e9" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;06/06/2003&nbsp;: 2:55:21 PM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Nothing specific to add, and it could have already been stated, but the value in knowing this information is in that you can "Set up" the rampage list and can't "Set up" the agro list as the Rampage list is a static list created when initial agro is established. Agro list can and does change throughout the life of the fight.</span></font></td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Etadanik Mistmorgue</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;06/06/2003&nbsp;: 1:46:06 PM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Just to add something about flurry and mob backstabs: mobs CAN flurry backstabs.  This is, to my knowledge, due to the way backstabs are handled for mobs, in that there's no backstabbing modifier (as with rogues), but that it is simply a special attack (with a set damage) the mob uses when a target's back is turned.  <br /><br />I've personally had a mob flurry about 4-5 backstabs for 500+ damage on me in one round of combat + normal melee damage.  Suffice to say, I died instantly.<br /></span></font></td>
              </tr>
