                <td bgcolor="#ECECEC" valign="top"><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;06/06/2003&nbsp;: 10:51:41 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> In my experience, youre right in Enrage.<br /><br /><b>Rampage</b> (I may have misunderstood your description)<br /><br />The mob does continues to attack the Main Tank, while at the same time executing a series of short term attacks on the NEXT person on the hate list.  All the while it never stops its focus on the Main Tank, it just gets in a few shots on another player (the second person who gets on the haste list from the start).  This person tanking enrage might be on the bottom of the hate list, but they were the second one there initially so they will be tanking the enrage attacks until the mob dies or they do.  It's important for a tank type to be the enrage tank so it's not one of your clerics.<br /><br /><b>Flurry</b> (of attacks)<br /><br />This is pretty easy to understand, when a mob Flurries it just attacks about 10 times in about 2 seconds, when normally it would attack twice, or quad, a flurry is just a LOT of attacks on the same person who has agro.  I may be wrong about this, I don't know if flurries can hit everyone around the mob or not, I have only watched a Flurry be executed on the main tank (and the mob will move to it's next target if it kills that person with the flurry of course).<br /></span></font></td>
